</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="486" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[1445,2653,1980,3073]" pageId="5" pageNumber="486">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1446,1700,2020,2049]" pageId="5" pageNumber="486">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body ¢.39 cm, tail ¢.39 cm; weight c.1 kg. Like the Small Sulawesi Cuscus (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1858" box="[1691,1846,2055,2088]" class="Mammalia" family="Phalangeridae" genus="Strigocuscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diprotodontia" pageId="5" pageNumber="486" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="celebensis">S. celebensis</taxonomicName>
), the Small Sangihe Cuscusis a small phalangerid without distinct dorsal stripe. The Small Sangihe Cuscus averages larger in body size, has a larger skull and teeth, and more colorful fur than the Small Sulawesi Cuscus. Fur of the Small Sangihe Cuscus is more prominently tipped with golden highlights, and face, limbs, and tail are yellowish, contrasting with the golden-brown back (uniform gray-brown in the Small Sulawesi Cuscus).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
